}
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs18 \cf1 \i0 
In each of these cases, an even stronger argument than that made in the dissent could be made to the effect that since each of these bills had been signed by the President, the very officer who challenged them had consented to their becoming law and it was therefore no concern of this Court that the law violated the Constitution. Just as the dissent contends that \u8220\'3fthe States are fully able to protect their own interests . . . ,\u8221\'3f Post, at 2486, it could have been contended that the President, armed with the mandate of a national constituency and with the veto power, was able to protect His own interests. Nonetheless, in both cases the laws were held unconstitutional, because they trenched on the authority of the Executive Branch.
